body:
Using `Assets::iter` to get an `AssetId`, then converting the resulting `AssetId` into a strong handle is not possible.

I would have expected the following to work, but it doesn't:
```rust
fn deduplicate(
    In(new_asset): In<A>,
    mut assets: ResMut<Assets<A>>,
    server: Res<AssetServer>,
) -> Handle<A> {
    match assets.iter().find(|(id, a)| **a == new_asset) {
        None =>  assets.insert(new_asset),
        Some(duplicate) => server.get_id_handle(duplicate).unwrap(),
    }
}
```

It doesn't work because `server.get_id_handle` only support handles that were loaded from an `AssetServer`, which is not specified in the `get_id_handle` docs (since it has no docs).

### Expected solution

A method on `Assets` that returns a strong handle given an `AssetId<A>`.

### Discussed in https://github.com/bevyengine/bevy/discussions/11743

<div type='discussions-op-text'>

<sup>Originally posted by **thmxv** February  6, 2024</sup>
Hi,

I build Asset from code and add them using Assets<A>.add(). However, I would like to search for possible duplicate and get a handle to the duplicate, if it exists, before doing the add.

```rust
let new_asset = MyAssetType {
    data: 1,
};
// TODO: Do not call following code if asset is a duplicate of an existing one
// set the handle to the pre-existing asset
let asset_handle = my_assets.add(new_asset);
```

I spent a lot of time reading the doc and trying some code. I can find duplicates with:

```rust
my_asserts.iter().find(|(id, a)| **a == new_asset)
```
But I do not manage to get a strong handle to the existing asset.

Am I doing something wrong? Is there way to do what I want?</div>
